Abstract

This R Markdown template is for writing an Harrisburg University dissertation. The template is built using Yihui Xie’s bookdown package, with heavy inspiration from Chester Ismay’s thesisdown and the OxThesis  aTeX template (most recently adapted by John McManigle). This template’s sample content include illustrations of how to write a thesis in R Markdown, and largely follows the structure from this R Markdown workshophttps://ulyngs.github.io/rmarkdown-workshop-2019/. Congratulations for taking a step further into the lands of open, reproducible science by writing your thesis using a tool that allows you to transparently include tables and dynamically generated plots directly from the underlying data. 3 Research Status

This chapter details where you are going to publish your portfolio works. You need the working name, targeted publisher, current status, and timeline.

This chapter will be very short and only needed as part of your proposal.

The following sections detail the targeted publications.

  1. “My 1st Publication”, Chapter 4
  2. “My 2nd Publication”, Chapter 5
  3. “My 3rd Publication”, Chapter 6

Chapter 4 will be submitted to the Datahttps://www.mdpi.com/journal/data for consideration in their January Issue. Chapter 5 will be submitted to the Datahttps://www.mdpi.com/journal/data for consideration in their January Issue. Chapter 6 will be submitted to the Datahttps://www.mdpi.com/journal/data for consideration in their January Issue.

NOTE: The chapters in your publications are sub-chapters in your dissertation. This means you need to add a \(2^{nd}\) # in front of your headings in those files.

7 Conclusion

If we don’t want Conclusion to have a chapter number next to it, we can add the {-} attribute.

More info

And here’s some other random info: the first paragraph after a chapter title or section head shouldn’t be indented, because indents are to tell the reader that you’re starting a new paragraph. Since that’s obvious after a chapter or section title, proper typesetting doesn’t add an indent there.
